WEBVTT

00:01.126 --> 00:02.920
ANNOUNCER:
Last season, on Love, Victor...

00:02.920 --> 00:05.255
ARMANDO: This is it, Salazars.
Our beautiful new home.

00:05.255 --> 00:06.340
VICTOR:
Dear Simon,

00:06.340 --> 00:09.510
you don't know me, but today
was my first day at Creekwood High.

00:09.510 --> 00:12.262
[bell rings]
I thought I'd finally get the chance
to be myself.

00:12.262 --> 00:13.764
To figure out who I really am.

00:13.764 --> 00:16.391
‐ Today, you paint the brush strokes
that define who you want to be.

00:16.391 --> 00:18.352
‐ Hey, new kid.
‐ Easy, Lake.

00:18.352 --> 00:20.270
‐ Is there a girl back home, or...?

00:20.270 --> 00:23.982
VICTOR: But my first day
didn't go exactly as planned.

00:23.982 --> 00:26.652
‐ Nope. No girl back in Texas.

00:26.652 --> 00:29.279
‐ Got it.
‐ You just made Mia Brooks blush.

00:29.279 --> 00:30.989
VICTOR: I ended up
connecting with this girl Mia,

00:30.989 --> 00:33.825
and she's great.
Sexuality's a spectrum. Right?

00:33.825 --> 00:35.953
FELIX: You think you can put in
a good word with Lake?

00:35.953 --> 00:36.995
I kind of have a thing for her.

00:36.995 --> 00:40.082
You deserve a guy
who would sacrifice everything.

00:40.082 --> 00:42.543
VICTOR: While my friend Felix
started a romance of his own...

00:42.543 --> 00:44.920
LAKE: You're my sexy little secret.
‐ A forbidden romance.

00:44.920 --> 00:47.172
ANDREW: How come we never talked about
what happened between us?

00:47.172 --> 00:49.174
‐ 'Cause there's nothing to talk about.
It was a mistake.

00:49.174 --> 00:50.926
VICTOR:
Things with my family were messy.

00:50.926 --> 00:51.969
PILAR:
This is why we moved?

00:51.969 --> 00:54.638
Because you did whatever
the hell you did with Dad's boss?

00:54.638 --> 00:57.057
VICTOR: Which made it harder
for me to deal with my own stuff.

00:57.057 --> 00:58.308
‐ Everything okay?

00:59.560 --> 01:01.687
‐ I'm sorry. I'm so sorry, Benji.

01:01.687 --> 01:03.188
I like guys.

01:03.188 --> 01:04.940
FELIX:
This doesn't change anything between us,

01:04.940 --> 01:06.191
but telling Mia's gonna suck.

01:06.191 --> 01:08.277
VICTOR: I just want to give Mia
an amazing night at the dance,

01:08.277 --> 01:09.319
and then I'll tell her the truth tomorrow.

01:09.319 --> 01:12.573
‐ The truth is, Felix Weston
makes me happy.

01:12.573 --> 01:13.991
[crowd cheering, clapping]

01:13.991 --> 01:15.993
BENJI: I want to be with someone
who makes me feel like

01:15.993 --> 01:17.494
I can just be myself.

01:17.494 --> 01:18.787
That's how you make me feel.

01:18.787 --> 01:22.332
VICTOR: And then the most
amazing thing happened with Benji.

01:22.332 --> 01:24.126
But it broke Mia's heart.

01:24.126 --> 01:25.961
‐ All this time, was any of it real?

01:25.961 --> 01:27.713
PILAR: She found out, didn't she?

01:27.713 --> 01:30.465
‐ I've been going through something,
and I want to explain it to you.

01:30.465 --> 01:32.134
I have something I need
to tell you guys.

01:32.134 --> 01:33.093
ISABEL:
We're separating.

01:33.093 --> 01:34.553
After what we've been through this year,

01:34.553 --> 01:36.513
we just needed to take a breather.

01:36.513 --> 01:37.806
‐ I'm gonna change.

01:37.806 --> 01:40.100
‐ Wait. Victor,
what were you gonna tell us?

01:43.645 --> 01:44.813
‐ Nothing.

01:54.656 --> 01:55.616
No.

01:56.450 --> 01:57.743
Not nothing.

01:59.661 --> 02:01.705
Mom... Dad...

02:05.209 --> 02:06.335
I'm gay.

02:26.146 --> 02:27.523
‐ I love you.

02:33.904 --> 02:35.113
‐ Um...

02:36.240 --> 02:38.659
I'm sorry. I, I don't, um...

02:39.993 --> 02:41.537
But what about Mia?

02:43.372 --> 02:45.791
‐ Well, I, I, uh...
[clears throat]

02:45.791 --> 02:49.294
thought that if I could make it work
with any girl, um...

02:49.294 --> 02:50.462
it'd be Mia.

02:51.338 --> 02:53.715
But I was wrong.

02:55.342 --> 02:56.760
‐ And how do you...

02:58.011 --> 02:59.179
I mean...

03:00.597 --> 03:03.267
[exhales] When did you decide this?

03:03.267 --> 03:06.979
‐ I didn't decide it. I just... am it.

03:12.442 --> 03:14.528
Mom, could you please say something?

03:14.528 --> 03:18.949
‐ I think, um,
that we should get some rest.

03:21.076 --> 03:22.953
And we can talk about it tomorrow.

03:29.042 --> 03:30.794
‐ Um...

03:30.794 --> 03:32.296
[sighs]

03:44.558 --> 03:45.767
‐ I'm sorry.

03:46.977 --> 03:48.228
Are you okay?

03:49.479 --> 03:52.357
‐ Yeah. Yeah. I'm fine. Uh...

03:53.984 --> 03:56.945
I'm sure they just need some time.

04:06.997 --> 04:08.707
[sighs]

04:09.124 --> 04:11.668
‐ ♪ Somebody to tell me
it'll be all right ♪

04:11.668 --> 04:14.588
♪ Somebody to tell me
it'll be just fine ♪

04:14.588 --> 04:18.008
♪ If someone has been there before,
say it right now ♪

04:18.008 --> 04:20.844
♪ 'Cause I just need to hear it ♪

04:22.679 --> 04:25.974
♪

04:28.519 --> 04:30.437
‐ ♪ Yeah ♪
‐ ♪ Yeah ♪

04:30.437 --> 04:32.105
‐ ♪ Yeah ♪
‐ ♪ Yeah, yeah ♪

04:32.105 --> 04:34.525
VICTOR: Hey Simon,
happy last week of summer.

04:34.525 --> 04:37.236
I'd thought I'd give you
an end of summer update.

04:37.236 --> 04:40.030
Things are still pretty weird with my mom.

04:40.030 --> 04:41.949
I mean, she knows I'm gay.

04:41.949 --> 04:43.951
I even told her that Benji
is my boyfriend...

04:44.493 --> 04:46.912
Hey. Uh...

04:46.912 --> 04:49.039
Benji and I are hanging out with
Lake and Felix after work,

04:49.039 --> 04:50.958
so I, I won't be home till late.

04:50.958 --> 04:54.628
‐ Okay. Have fun with your friends.

04:54.628 --> 04:57.297
VICTOR: But we never actually
talk about any of it.

05:00.926 --> 05:04.054
Things are a little bit better
with my dad. But still awkward.

05:04.054 --> 05:05.931
ARMANDO :
So, I know it's not huge, but, uh, hey,

05:05.931 --> 05:08.141
the place, it gets great light.

05:10.269 --> 05:12.688
Huh? I mean, unless it's trash day,

05:12.688 --> 05:14.982
'cause then, well,
a dumpster blocks the window.

05:14.982 --> 05:16.900
VICTOR: He's been all fake cheery
about the separation,

05:16.900 --> 05:18.735
even though I know
he's totally bummed about it.

05:18.735 --> 05:21.071
‐ Oh, you, uh... you headed to work?

05:21.071 --> 05:23.824
Hey. Tell the Benji‐meister I said, "Sup!"

05:23.824 --> 05:25.576
VICTOR:
He's channeling his discomfort

05:25.576 --> 05:27.494
with me having a boyfriend
into nicknames.

05:27.494 --> 05:29.705
‐ Benjamin Button. Right?

05:29.705 --> 05:31.999
Ben‐venido!
[chuckling]

05:31.999 --> 05:33.667
‐ Yeah. I'll, I'll tell him.

05:33.667 --> 05:34.960
[chuckles]

05:38.380 --> 05:41.049
But it's not all bad.

05:41.049 --> 05:42.843
‐ ♪ I'm kind of a mess ♪

05:42.843 --> 05:45.512
VICTOR: Benji is the actual best.

05:46.180 --> 05:48.682
‐ ♪ It's what you do to me ♪

05:51.143 --> 05:53.729
VICTOR:
We aren't Instagram official or anything.

05:54.646 --> 05:57.191
No one from school even knows
we're a thing except our best friends.

05:58.400 --> 06:00.319
It's kind of been great that way.

06:00.319 --> 06:02.529
Like we're in our own
little summer bubble,

06:02.529 --> 06:05.532
and we have this totally perfect secret.

06:05.532 --> 06:08.368
And I gotta say, the bubble is hot.

06:10.495 --> 06:12.414
‐ Whoops! Yeah, no, don't, don't mind me.

06:12.414 --> 06:15.000
I'm just, uh, looking for
the caramel syrup.

06:15.000 --> 06:18.879
Hey, do you guys call it car‐mel,
or care‐a‐mel?

06:18.879 --> 06:21.548
[knocking]
LAKE: Hi. Hi. Sorry.

06:21.548 --> 06:23.008
Uh, yeah, I know you guys are horny,

06:23.008 --> 06:25.552
but anyone gonna make
my sugar‐free iced mocha?

06:25.552 --> 06:26.970
‐ On it.
‐ Yeah, right away.

06:27.930 --> 06:29.556
As for Mia,

06:29.556 --> 06:32.142
we haven't actually
talked since the dance.

06:32.142 --> 06:34.186
She took off the second school ended

06:34.186 --> 06:36.897
to be a camp counselor
in North Carolina.

06:36.897 --> 06:39.942
‐ Caroline! Hey, put your top back on!

06:39.942 --> 06:42.027
This is not that kind of camp!

06:42.027 --> 06:45.405
VICTOR: I just really hope
she doesn't hate me forever.

06:45.405 --> 06:48.825
But the weird thing is,
despite everything,

06:48.825 --> 06:51.828
this has kind of been
the best summer of my life.

06:53.997 --> 06:55.624
‐ What?

06:55.624 --> 06:56.834
‐ Nothing.

06:57.668 --> 06:58.752
‐ Weirdo.

07:01.880 --> 07:03.257
Hey, so school starts Monday.

07:03.257 --> 07:06.677
We should probably talk about
what we're gonna tell everyone.

07:06.677 --> 07:08.095
‐ Yeah. I know.

07:09.638 --> 07:12.516
I want to tell people. I'm ready.

07:12.516 --> 07:16.436
No more hiding who I am.
Or who I'm into.

07:19.940 --> 07:23.277
FELIX: So, last weekend
before school starts.

07:23.277 --> 07:24.653
What are we thinking?

07:24.653 --> 07:26.864
There's a ten part docuseries

07:26.864 --> 07:28.782
about human trafficking,

07:28.782 --> 07:32.411
and Atlanta Weekly
said it was grueling...

07:32.411 --> 07:33.954
but important.

07:33.954 --> 07:36.665
‐ Or we could go to Lake Lanier.

07:36.665 --> 07:38.667
Finally have that bonfire
we've been talking about all summer.

07:38.667 --> 07:40.544
‐ Hmm. I pick Victor's thing.

07:40.544 --> 07:41.962
‐ Yes.
VICTOR: Great.

07:41.962 --> 07:43.964
‐ But, can we do it on Saturday?

07:43.964 --> 07:45.048
Mia comes home on Sunday,

07:45.048 --> 07:47.384
and I love you guys,
but Mia's my best friend

07:47.384 --> 07:49.887
and if she's still mad at you, so am I.

07:49.887 --> 07:51.597
Hos before homos.

07:51.597 --> 07:54.391
‐ Understood. Oh, and also,
can we do after dinner?

07:54.391 --> 07:56.643
Adrian's going to my dad's,
and Mom's making pollo guisado.

07:56.643 --> 07:58.478
‐ Ooh! Love her pollo guisado.

07:58.478 --> 08:00.314
‐ It's heaven on rice.

08:00.314 --> 08:02.232
‐ Sounds delicious.

08:04.067 --> 08:06.528
‐ You still haven't been over to Victor's?

08:06.528 --> 08:09.489
‐ Nope. Not since we started dating.

08:09.489 --> 08:11.158
We always hang out at my house.

08:11.158 --> 08:13.410
‐ You know my mom.
You, you guys know how she is.

08:13.410 --> 08:15.954
‐ If she's not ready,
she's not ready. It's fine.

08:19.625 --> 08:22.336
‐ You know what?
Why don't you all come over for dinner?

08:22.336 --> 08:23.921
I mean...

08:23.921 --> 08:25.839
how am I supposed to be out
to all of Creekwood on Monday

08:25.839 --> 08:28.091
if I can't even have
my boyfriend over for dinner?

08:28.091 --> 08:31.929
♪

08:35.432 --> 08:38.185
‐ Ugh.
‐ That will be $800.

08:38.185 --> 08:41.688
‐ You know, I hope you are this good
at business in real life,

08:41.688 --> 08:44.358
so you can put me in
one of those fancy old folks' homes

08:44.358 --> 08:46.735
with the make‐your‐own omelet stations.

08:46.735 --> 08:49.279
‐ Mom, you need to dream bigger.
‐ Nah.

08:49.279 --> 08:50.989
[door opens]

08:50.989 --> 08:52.616
Hey, honey.
[door closes]

08:52.616 --> 08:54.284
Did you have fun with your friends?

08:54.284 --> 08:55.994
‐ Yeah. Um,

08:55.994 --> 08:58.205
I invited them over for dinner,
if that's okay.

08:58.205 --> 08:59.790
‐ Of course.

08:59.790 --> 09:02.167
‐ Cool. Um, Benji's coming, too.

09:03.085 --> 09:04.127
‐ Oh.

09:05.587 --> 09:06.630
Great.

09:07.339 --> 09:08.298
‐ Cool.

09:15.305 --> 09:18.976
VERONICA:
I need a little twisty piece...

09:18.976 --> 09:21.395
HAROLD: Yeah, right there in front of you.
A little twisty...

09:21.395 --> 09:22.938
VERONICA: No, it's right there‐‐
[exhales]

09:22.938 --> 09:24.147
HAROLD:
What are you talking about?

09:24.147 --> 09:26.358
It's the little screw.
VERONICA: This. No, this. Look.

09:26.358 --> 09:30.028
This is a little twisty...

09:30.028 --> 09:34.867
HAROLD: Well, excuse me. I didn't realize
you had a Master's in building cribs.

09:34.867 --> 09:35.909
‐ No?
‐ No.

09:35.909 --> 09:38.996
[both murmuring, kissing]

09:38.996 --> 09:40.414
‐ Hi, guys.
[Veronica gasps]

09:41.123 --> 09:42.332
Surprise!

09:42.332 --> 09:43.876
HAROLD: Oh!
‐ I'm home early.

09:43.876 --> 09:46.086
‐ Mia. Welcome home!
‐ What?

09:47.671 --> 09:49.298
You told me you weren't
coming till tomorrow.

09:49.298 --> 09:51.675
MIA: Yeah, well, we packed up
the bunks a day early.
‐ Aah...

09:51.675 --> 09:54.052
MIA:
So we decided to drive home today.

09:54.052 --> 09:55.387
HAROLD: All right.
MIA and VERONICA: Hi.

09:55.387 --> 09:57.097
[Mia laughs]
‐ Welcome back.

09:57.097 --> 09:58.473
I wish I'd known you were coming.

09:58.473 --> 10:00.934
We were gonna get your room ready.
‐ Yeah.

10:00.934 --> 10:02.895
‐ It's full of boxes of baby stuff.

10:04.021 --> 10:06.440
‐ It's fine. It's fine.
Don't worry about it. [chuckles]

10:07.816 --> 10:11.570
‐ So what do you think of Papi Palace?
Huh?

10:11.570 --> 10:13.405
And, uh, the place gets great light.

10:13.405 --> 10:15.240
Right? And, uh... oh!

10:15.240 --> 10:18.994
I was thinking maybe
we could watch Jumanji!

10:18.994 --> 10:20.370
Got it all queued up.

10:20.370 --> 10:22.456
‐ Eh. Heard it's problematic,

10:22.456 --> 10:25.375
because Jack Black plays a woman.

10:25.375 --> 10:27.211
Do you have any games?

10:27.211 --> 10:30.547
‐ Oh. Um, not really.

10:30.547 --> 10:32.007
‐ Can I go home?

10:32.007 --> 10:34.009
‐ What? No!

10:35.260 --> 10:36.261
Hey.

10:38.597 --> 10:40.933
If you could choose one thing

10:40.933 --> 10:44.102
to make this apartment more fun,
what would it be?

10:45.604 --> 10:49.316
♪

10:52.569 --> 10:53.612
‐ Mmm.

11:06.166 --> 11:09.044
♪

11:11.839 --> 11:13.215
[sighs]

11:16.343 --> 11:20.889
♪

11:25.978 --> 11:29.898
♪

11:32.526 --> 11:34.194
[foot pedal clatters]

11:44.913 --> 11:47.332
‐ Hey! We're here.

11:48.333 --> 11:50.002
‐ Hi.

11:50.002 --> 11:52.754
FELIX: Hey, Mrs. S.
LAKE: Ooh, love your top!

11:53.714 --> 11:55.090
‐ Good to see you, Mrs. Salazar.

11:55.090 --> 11:58.385
I‐I've heard so much
about your famous chicken.

11:58.385 --> 12:02.431
And a lot of other great things,
of course.

12:02.431 --> 12:05.225
‐ Thank you, Benji.

12:05.225 --> 12:07.853
Um, listen, guys,
I don't know what happened,

12:07.853 --> 12:09.771
but I went to go check on the food,

12:09.771 --> 12:11.190
and the stove must be broken or something,

12:11.190 --> 12:13.483
because it's totally burnt.

12:13.483 --> 12:16.570
It's just chicken... ash.

12:16.570 --> 12:20.073
So, why don't you guys go out?
Get some pizza... on me.

12:20.073 --> 12:21.366
[chuckles]

12:21.366 --> 12:23.076
[wallet clatters]

12:25.871 --> 12:27.414
‐ Why don't we just order delivery?

12:29.416 --> 12:32.961
‐ I... did not think of that.

12:32.961 --> 12:35.172
That sounds... good.

12:36.089 --> 12:36.965
‐ Great.

12:39.676 --> 12:41.303
[phone buzzes, jingles]

12:41.303 --> 12:42.763
‐ Oh, uh, excuse me. Sorry.

12:42.763 --> 12:44.306
This has been, uh, really great so far.

12:44.306 --> 12:46.975
I just gotta quickly
take this call outside.

12:46.975 --> 12:49.436
Away from here. [chuckles]

12:49.436 --> 12:50.979
‐ Let me show you around.

12:52.856 --> 12:56.026
‐ Mia. Hey.
‐ Hey.

12:57.569 --> 12:59.655
‐ I called you like a million times‐‐
‐ I've been off the grid‐‐

12:59.655 --> 13:01.240
‐ Oh. [laughs]

13:02.407 --> 13:04.952
‐ I just, I needed time to,
to clear my head.

13:04.952 --> 13:07.037
But I'm home now.

13:07.037 --> 13:11.375
And, um, my dad and Veronica
won't stop making out. [chuckles]

13:11.375 --> 13:15.587
Um, and I'm staring at a breast pump.
[laughs]

13:15.587 --> 13:17.214
Can I come over?

13:17.214 --> 13:20.050
‐ Wait, you're home?
I thought you were back tomorrow.

13:20.050 --> 13:21.176
Um...

13:22.469 --> 13:24.847
Well, I‐I'm actually at Victor's.

13:25.556 --> 13:28.225
‐ Oh. Cool.

13:28.225 --> 13:30.269
‐ Is that okay?

13:30.269 --> 13:33.313
Because if it's not,
I will leave right now.

13:33.313 --> 13:34.565
Queens before peens.

13:34.565 --> 13:37.359
I mean, you say the word
and I will ditch these gays

13:37.359 --> 13:39.486
like a corporation after Pride month.

13:39.486 --> 13:42.406
‐ Lake, it's fine.
Um, we'll hang tomorrow.

13:42.406 --> 13:45.075
‐ Yes, please. Um...

13:45.075 --> 13:49.121
But also, we're having a bonfire
at Lake Lanier tonight,

13:49.121 --> 13:51.623
and Victor and Benji will be there.

13:51.623 --> 13:55.043
But you should come.

13:55.043 --> 13:57.671
MIA:
Maybe. I'll think about it.

13:57.671 --> 13:58.839
Bye.

13:58.839 --> 14:00.424
[phone beeps]

14:02.092 --> 14:04.845
‐ The secret is two layers of sunscreen.

14:04.845 --> 14:07.347
Sunscreen, primer, sunscreen again.

14:07.347 --> 14:09.641
And then, only then, foundation.

14:09.641 --> 14:12.561
I call it the sunscreen sandwich.
Nobody steal that.

14:12.561 --> 14:14.104
[both chuckle]
VICTOR: Hey.

14:14.104 --> 14:16.648
I got some chips.
You know, until the pizza comes.

14:18.650 --> 14:20.736
Cool.
[Isabel clears throat]

14:21.862 --> 14:23.906
‐ Thanks.
[crunching]

14:26.241 --> 14:27.576
LAKE: Mmm...
BENJI: Mmm...

14:27.576 --> 14:28.869
‐ Hits the spot.

14:28.869 --> 14:30.787
‐ Mmm. So good.

14:30.787 --> 14:33.081
‐ This salsa homemade? [chuckles]

14:33.081 --> 14:35.584
‐ I love chips.

14:35.584 --> 14:36.919
[Isabel chuckles softly]

14:36.919 --> 14:39.171
‐ Mom, did you know Benji's in a band?

14:39.171 --> 14:41.798
He sings and plays guitar
and piano. Like you.

14:42.925 --> 14:47.012
‐ Um, yeah, actually my mom
just got a new job

14:47.012 --> 14:49.765
as the music director at
Saint Frances Church.

14:49.765 --> 14:50.933
BENJI:
Mmm.

14:50.933 --> 14:53.268
‐ You know Benji actually likes
a lot of the same music as you, Ma.

14:53.268 --> 14:56.146
Like, um, Billie Holiday.

14:56.146 --> 14:58.106
You love her, right?

14:58.106 --> 14:59.483
‐ Yes, I do.

15:01.360 --> 15:05.113
Felix, is it true that your job
at Brasstown is coming to end,

15:05.113 --> 15:07.616
because I absolutely love
your fruit smoothies.

15:07.616 --> 15:10.452
You really know your way around a mango.

15:10.452 --> 15:12.788
‐ Oh, well, uh, you know,
Benji, he, uh,

15:12.788 --> 15:15.249
he taught me everything I know.
Yeah. So, uh...

15:15.249 --> 15:19.127
I just, uh, follow his
instructions and hit puree. [chuckles]

15:19.753 --> 15:23.924
‐ Well, you are gonna have to give me
your recipe someday, Benji.

15:23.924 --> 15:26.134
‐ I mean, usually that's top secret.

15:26.134 --> 15:29.263
But for my boyfriend's mom,

15:29.263 --> 15:31.014
I'll make an exception.

15:32.891 --> 15:34.309
‐ [clears throat]
I've had too much salsa.

15:34.309 --> 15:38.105
Um, I've got this, like,
acidy reflux thing, so...

15:38.105 --> 15:39.523
I'm gonna let you guys hang...

15:39.523 --> 15:40.816
‐ Ma, you had, like, one chip.

15:40.816 --> 15:42.067
Why don't you just wait
to see if it passes?

15:42.067 --> 15:45.153
‐ Victor, if I said I don't feel good,
I don't feel good. Déjame, okay?

15:58.125 --> 16:00.002
‐ Why don't we just go
to that bonfire, yeah?

16:00.002 --> 16:01.378
‐ Yeah.
‐ Sounds good. Yeah.

16:01.378 --> 16:03.839
[Benji clears throat]
LAKE: Okay, so how long is the drive?

16:03.839 --> 16:05.799
‐ Hey.
FELIX: About an hour.

16:10.429 --> 16:13.015
‐ I can't believe you let me get a turtle.

16:13.015 --> 16:16.185
Pilar was right.
Guilty separated Dad is the best.

16:16.185 --> 16:17.561
‐ She said that?

16:17.561 --> 16:19.104
[sighs]
‐ I'm gonna call her Heather.

16:19.104 --> 16:20.731
‐ Why Heather?

16:20.731 --> 16:22.357
‐ Because it's a beautiful name.

16:24.484 --> 16:28.197
Wait, we need to go back.
We need another tank.

16:28.197 --> 16:30.240
‐ What? Why? This one's got everything.

16:30.240 --> 16:33.035
It's got plants, and a little rock
for her to sun herself.

16:33.660 --> 16:35.370
‐ Yeah, but we need two tanks.

16:35.370 --> 16:38.081
One for your place and one for mine.

16:38.081 --> 16:40.751
‐ Mijo, Heather's only gonna live
in my apartment.

16:41.627 --> 16:42.628
‐ Oh.

16:44.046 --> 16:46.048
Then I don't want her.

16:46.048 --> 16:47.758
‐ What? Why not?

16:48.550 --> 16:50.761
‐ I already miss you half the time.

16:50.761 --> 16:53.055
I don't need to miss a turtle, too.

16:55.057 --> 16:56.934
Let's just return her.

16:59.102 --> 17:00.437
‐ Adrian.

17:01.188 --> 17:05.442
♪

17:06.944 --> 17:08.570
[indistinct chatter]

17:13.450 --> 17:14.618
ANDREW:
Hungry much?

17:18.830 --> 17:20.290
‐ Hi, Andrew.

17:21.083 --> 17:22.584
‐ How was your summer?

17:22.584 --> 17:25.504
‐ I missed air conditioning.
[chuckles]

17:25.504 --> 17:28.799
And there was a week when my whole
cabin's periods synced up,

17:28.799 --> 17:30.968
and it turned into The Hunger Games.
‐ Wow.

17:30.968 --> 17:34.972
‐ [laughs] Um, but I mean,
other than that, pretty good.

17:41.019 --> 17:43.480
I got your care package.

17:43.480 --> 17:46.108
I'm sorry that I didn't respond.

17:46.108 --> 17:49.486
‐ Oh no, it's fine.
‐ No, it's not.

17:49.486 --> 17:52.698
Uh, but, um, between Victor being gay,

17:52.698 --> 17:55.576
and my dad getting engaged,

17:55.576 --> 17:57.452
and Veronica getting pregnant,

17:57.452 --> 18:00.664
I... I just wanted to take the summer

18:00.664 --> 18:03.292
to figure out where I fit here.

18:03.292 --> 18:06.712
‐ And? Well, did you figure it out?

18:06.712 --> 18:09.631
‐ Didn't even come close.
[chuckles]

18:09.631 --> 18:11.383
I‐‐
LUCY: Hey. Sorry I'm late.

18:14.303 --> 18:17.014
‐ Oh, do you know‐‐
MIA: Lucy, right?

18:17.014 --> 18:19.308
Um, you're friends with Benji.

18:19.308 --> 18:22.603
Uh, and we, we had English together
freshman year.

18:22.603 --> 18:24.646
‐ Yes! Ms. Smuckler!
[Mia laughs]

18:24.646 --> 18:26.857
Why was she always assigning
those erotic poems?

18:26.857 --> 18:31.236
‐ Yeah, if I had to read one more
haiku about a quivering flower...

18:31.236 --> 18:32.779
Uh... [inhales]

18:32.779 --> 18:35.699
So, uh, when did you guys...

18:35.699 --> 18:38.452
‐ Uh, Steve Danahey's
Fourth of July party.

18:38.452 --> 18:42.039
‐ Huh.
‐ Weird, right? I'm so not into jocks.

18:42.039 --> 18:44.416
And yet somehow this
walking protein shake

18:44.416 --> 18:45.876
wormed his way into my heart.

18:45.876 --> 18:48.712
‐ Well, the heart wants what it wants.

18:48.712 --> 18:50.964
And mine currently wants this...

18:50.964 --> 18:53.550
Uh, shrimp lo mein, so I'm gonna...

18:53.550 --> 18:55.219
I'll see you at school.

18:56.845 --> 18:58.472
‐ Wanna go?
‐ Yeah.

18:59.056 --> 19:02.518
‐ ♪ Ooh ooh ooh ooh ♪

19:02.518 --> 19:06.855
♪ Ooh ooh, ooh ooh ooh ♪

19:06.855 --> 19:10.943
♪ Ooh ooh ooh ooh ♪

19:16.865 --> 19:18.742
‐ Hey, guys.
ARMANDO: Hey.

19:18.742 --> 19:20.452
‐ What is all this stuff?

19:20.452 --> 19:23.705
‐ Mom, meet Heather. My new turtle.

19:23.705 --> 19:26.542
She's gonna live here,
and at Dad's apartment.

19:26.542 --> 19:29.294
Come on, Heather.
‐ Okay...

19:29.294 --> 19:32.714
‐ Yeah, I know. I, uh,
I wanted my apartment to be fun,

19:32.714 --> 19:35.843
and, uh, kinda spiraled from there, so...

19:37.177 --> 19:38.846
‐ How is your new place?

19:38.846 --> 19:40.264
‐ Oh, my place? It's...

19:40.264 --> 19:43.308
Yeah, my place is great.
Yeah, it's good. It's, um...

19:47.062 --> 19:48.647
It's depressing as hell.

19:50.983 --> 19:53.318
‐ We're doing the right thing, right?

19:54.027 --> 19:57.030
The separation...
‐ I think so. I...

19:58.073 --> 19:59.575
We were stuck.

19:59.575 --> 20:03.495
We were stuck in a cycle of just
fighting and guilt tripping...

20:03.495 --> 20:05.372
Wasn't fair to us.

20:05.372 --> 20:07.791
Right? It definitely
wasn't fair to the kids.

20:07.791 --> 20:09.751
‐ Yeah.

20:09.751 --> 20:11.253
Yeah, I know.

20:12.379 --> 20:15.382
So... Benji came over tonight.

20:17.217 --> 20:20.220
We were all supposed to
have dinner together...

20:20.220 --> 20:24.850
‐ Hmm.
‐ But then I saw him and Victor
acting like a couple and I, I...

20:26.059 --> 20:29.563
‐ Yeah, I, I know.
I get it. It's... it's a lot.

20:29.563 --> 20:30.856
It's, it's a lot for me, too,

20:30.856 --> 20:34.193
and it's lot for, for me
to wrap my head around.

20:35.110 --> 20:36.862
‐ Do you think you ever will?

20:38.238 --> 20:39.948
‐ Of course.

20:39.948 --> 20:44.411
Isa, he's my son, and it's who he is.

20:44.411 --> 20:45.746
I have to.

20:46.997 --> 20:48.207
We both do.

20:50.042 --> 20:53.921
♪

20:57.883 --> 20:59.968
BENJI: Okay, I think we got it‐‐
‐ Oh, wait! No.

20:59.968 --> 21:01.678
I wanna‐‐
I wanna do the lighter fluid! Please?

21:01.678 --> 21:03.430
‐ Go for it.
FELIX: Thank you. All right.

21:03.430 --> 21:04.598
[Lake chuckles]

21:07.476 --> 21:09.478
Okay, I'm scared.
I don't want my face to burn off.

21:09.478 --> 21:12.272
My mom says I have the jawline
of a young Hilary Swank.

21:12.272 --> 21:14.358
‐ Aw, Felix, just do it.
‐ Come on, man. Come on, just do it.

21:16.318 --> 21:18.403
[fluid pouring]
‐ Whoa!

21:18.403 --> 21:20.072
[all exclaiming, chattering]

21:23.200 --> 21:24.576
All righty.

21:26.912 --> 21:30.207
‐ Hey, Felix, let's go get the fireworks
from the car, huh?

21:30.207 --> 21:31.917
‐ But it's cozy.

21:31.917 --> 21:33.836
‐ I'll make it worth your while.

21:34.753 --> 21:36.255
[laughs]

21:38.632 --> 21:41.301
‐ Those two are kind of perfect together.

21:41.301 --> 21:42.344
‐ Yeah.

21:51.311 --> 21:52.521
‐ Hey.

21:53.647 --> 21:56.149
I'm sorry things didn't go well today.

21:57.025 --> 21:58.277
With your mom.

22:00.612 --> 22:02.072
‐ It's okay.

22:02.072 --> 22:04.157
I'm sure things will
get better eventually.

22:05.993 --> 22:09.121
‐ You know, you don't
have to pretend everything's okay

22:09.121 --> 22:11.582
when we talk about how shitty
your mom was being.

22:13.166 --> 22:16.753
I mean, she can barely
look at us together.

22:16.753 --> 22:19.006
She won't let you tell Adrian
that you're gay.

22:19.006 --> 22:20.883
You're allowed to be pissed off.

22:24.094 --> 22:26.763
‐ My mom has put my family
through so much‐‐

22:27.639 --> 22:32.269
You know, with the move, and the affair,
and the separation, and...

22:34.813 --> 22:37.232
I forgave her because she's my mom.

22:38.192 --> 22:41.361
But I tell her I'm gay, and now
she can barely even look at me.

22:42.821 --> 22:44.239
‐ Victor...

22:44.239 --> 22:46.909
‐ And on Monday we start school.

22:46.909 --> 22:49.453
And part of me is so excited

22:49.453 --> 22:51.914
to yell from the rooftops
that you're my boyfriend.

22:54.166 --> 22:56.752
But there's another part of me that is...

22:56.752 --> 22:58.086
completely terrified.

22:59.379 --> 23:00.714
‐ I understand.

23:05.427 --> 23:09.306
VICTOR: I just wish
things could be as simple as...

23:09.306 --> 23:12.643
you and me, Lake and Felix,

23:12.643 --> 23:14.561
in our perfect little summer bubble.

23:14.561 --> 23:16.813
‐ No, Victor. It is that simple.

23:17.898 --> 23:20.776
You and me. That's what matters.

23:20.776 --> 23:24.530
School... Parents... It's all just noise.

23:25.822 --> 23:29.159
As long as we remember that,
we'll be okay.

23:31.620 --> 23:32.788
‐ Okay.

23:36.166 --> 23:39.878
♪

23:44.508 --> 23:47.344
LAKE: Hey, break it up, Romeo and Romeo.
[Felix laughs]

23:47.344 --> 23:49.179
Hey. Got some fireworks.

23:49.179 --> 23:51.682
‐ Yeah, look at these.
‐ Aah... whoa.

23:51.682 --> 23:55.519
[all chattering]
♪ "Hide and Seek"
